                  <handDesc>
                     
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Mediocre</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black; red (vermillion).</seg>
                        Scribe: Näṣṣärä ʾAb. The name of the
                        scribe Näṣṣärä ʾAb is mentioned in the colophon. The same scribe copied Mss.
                        EHPP-004, EHPP-013.<date>19th century</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ሰላ፡</abbr> for <expan>ሰላም፡ </expan> (e.g., <locus target="#20vb">20vb</locus> l.9, 21rb l.6, 21vb l.4)</item>
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ሰንበ፡</abbr> for <expan>ሰንበት፡ </expan> (e.g., <locus target="#20vb">20vb</locus> l.3, 21rb l.1, 21vb l.6)</item>
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ሰን፡</abbr> for <expan>ሰንበት፡ </expan> (esp. <locus target="#21rb">21rb</locus> l.10).</item>
                        </list>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Nomina sacra; name of the donor (and his relatives)
                           and the scribe.
 Four lines (in both columns) in the incipit page of
                           Text I (fol. 3r), divided into two groups alternating with black
                           lines;
 the first two lines in the incipit of Text II (fol. 20va);
                           
 the first three lines of incipit of Text III (fol. 22ra); 
 the
                           words sanbat (and its abbreviation “sanba”), sanbatawit, ba-sanbat, salām
                           (and its abbreviation “säla”), säbḥat, ʾo-fǝquranǝyä (fol. 17rb).
                           Elements of Ethiopic numbers, of punctuation signs and text
                           dividers.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The handwriting tends to square shapes,
                        broad strokes, the upper horizontal elements of the letters stricktly
                        parallel to the ruled
                        line.</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic"> - The markers of the 6th order of the
                        letters እ and ክ are very pronounced and
                        distinguishable.</handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic"> - The loop marker of the 7th order in
                        ቶ is set up directly at the horizontal stroke (<locus target="#18rb">18rb</locus>).</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
